description.text:
This is a calibration set that includes three circles, and is meant to be used to calibrate as many settings as possible at once.
One circle is solid to replace a calibration cube (print at 100% infill), one has only a thin wall, and one has a slightly thicker wall with a bridge covering the top. All three are printed at once, which lets you to test your reversal settings and also gives the parts time to cool while the others are printing.
I've been using this set for a while (every time I need to recalibrate for some reason), and it seems to test more characteristics faster than any other set I've tried.

comments.text: Print with 100% infill. The solid circle will serve the purpose of a calibration cube to help you dial in your flow rate. The one that's closed only on the top tests bridging, and the one that's open at both ends tests thin walls to see if you can print small features accurately with your layer height and thread width settings. Also, if they're not round, you know you have backlash.

Notes: The iPod bracket was printed with the side edge down. The swivels were printed with the large flat side down (pivot hole up/down).

The dove tail joint is very tight so I didn't need glue.  I needed to file the top of both sides a bit for it to slide in.  I put the swivel flush to the edge of the bracket so the wing nut would not hit the bracket (see pictures).  I had to drill the swivel hole to size, and used a small round file to touch up the hole for the rod.  The rod is slid in the bottom and a small zip tie hold the rod to the swivel tight.
Slide the bracket on and off the iPod from the bottom so it will not hit the camera lens or any of the side buttons.

I used a Caliper Micrometer to measure the iPod then created the model.  The iPod model was used to remove the profile from the bracket.  The bracket was scaled a bit larger so the iPod would slide through but firmly hold the iPod.  I had to make a few 10 layer tests adjusting the scaling to get the fit right.
I made this in 3 pieces to give it the best strength and so each piece can be made without supports.

title: Operant Conditioning Chamber
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
An operant conditioning chamber for rats. The operant chamber or "Skinner box" was invented by American psychologist B. F. Skinner during the early 1930s. It is used in psychological laboratories to study in a controlled situation the effects of environmental variables on the probability of a relatively simple response known as operant. In a simple arrangement, operant learning can be studied by presenting a reinforcing event (e.g., food or water) every time a rat presses a metal lever. In these particular chambers, rats can also be trained to press the lever only when a stimulus (e.g., a light) is presented. Numerous principles of behavior have been discovered in the operant chamber. Many of these are the basis for behavioral psychotherapy. These inexpensive 3D-printed operant chambers are used as teaching tools during the undergraduate courses of Learning and Behavior Analysis imparted by Dr. Rogelio Escobar at the National Autonomous University of Mexico (UNAM). Read more about this project: http://3dprint.com/106669/3d-printed-lab-equipment/
http://analisisdelaconducta.net/?page_id=496 All parts are printed in PLA because it is a non-toxic material. A layer height of 0.3 mm and a 20% fill density are recommended for the panels. A 0.2 mm resolution is recommended for the lock mechanism and hinges. No support material is necessary. I like printing the grid-holding parts using white PLA and the rest of the parts using gray PLA, but you could use any color you like. A file in AutoCAD format (Acrylic_Walls.dwg) includes three walls for the chamber. These must be laser cut in 3-mm clear acrylic. Red lines in the drawing represent cuts. You will need also the following materials: 15 – Stainless steel rods (8 mm diameter x 210 mm in length) . These can be obtained from any 3D printer-part supplier. 1 – 10 mm LED with holder. This LED is used as houselight. I like Adafruit’s diffused white LEDs (https://www.adafruit.com/products/846). An LED Plastic holder (https://www.adafruit.com/products/2171) fit perfectly in the chamber. 4 – #6-32 x 3/4 in. Machine Flat Phillips Screws with nuts. These are used to attach the parts holding the steel rods to the base of the chamber. 24 – #6-32 x 1/2 in. Machine Round Combo Screws with nuts. These are use to secure the panels and the hinges. 1- LED illuminated pushbutton - 30 mm round (https://www.adafruit.com/products/492). This is not actually used as a button but as a light above the lever. It is useful to present a visual stimulus. 3 - M3 x 10 mm screws. These keep the water/food tray in place. E6000 glue. The parts holding the steel rods, the lock mechanism, the small flange that keeps the door locked, and the water/food tray parts require glue. The panels can be glued together to make the chamber stronger. Follow the images to assemble the chamber. Blue parts are 3D printed, gray parts are laser cut acrylic, and white parts are stainless steel. Some 3D printed parts require sanding to facilitate assembly. The water pump to deliver liquid reinforcement can be found at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1247624 The lever can be found at: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1246025 This chamber is compatible with the Arduino-Visual Basic interface designed for operant research. The interface is described at: http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25649099 This project was funded through a grant from DGAPA UNAM (PAPIIT IN304615)

title: Specific Nexus 6 with Qi Charger Stand

description.text:
This is a very specific Phone Charging stand I made for my 2014 Motorola Nexus 6, the guts of a cheap Chinese Qi charger and a car window cell phone mount arm.
I took the guts out of a cheap Chinese Qi charger, put some electrical tape on the back of the electronics board and then folded it over super-glued it to the back of the Qi charging plate.
I then designed this phone holder to fit that Qi charger guts and my Nexus 6 along with holes to mount it onto a standard Car Window phone holder arm.
The Qi charger guts slide in from the top with the mini-USB connected at the bottom. You then plug in the power cord from underneath. Its a little tight getting my chubby fingers in there, but doable.
All this because I have a very small desk and nowhere to lay the charger down. So now I have it mounted to the side of my desk, out of the way, but still easily accessible. I made it extra thick and tough because it's hanging a $600 phone off the side of my desk!
I AM NOT RESPONSIBLE for any damage occurring to your phone, floor, or dog lying under it (or anything else) should you build this and it fails for whatever reason. Nor am I responsible for anything else that goes bad in your life...
Maybe you have a similar situation, or this will inspire you to make something like it...

This is a heated bed for a repstrap that is intended to be an alternative to a proffessionaly fabbed board.
I made this board because it is often hard to get large sheets of copper clad, and if it is, they are often more than one repstrapper may be willing to pay, especialy on a first machine.
Currently, the design below gets between 70C and 90C (under glass) when pulling ~5.79A @12v when etched onto 2oz/in copper clad.

-Measure your copper clad boards and cut each one individually to a size that allows for a properly sized square. -Once you have them cut, tape them together with some scotch tape in their square pattern with no gaps. -Next you use the toner transfer/iron on method of etch resist.
---If neccesary, use a coat of spray paint on one side of the board, in order to keep a solid copper layer on that side. (most spray paints will wipe off with acetone, but it is best to test this for your particular brand). Color does not matter. -Separate the boards by cutting the seems between the laminate board with a knife -Remove paper and etch normally. -Once all are etched, remove the toner and line up the laminate in it's original square shape, so that the traces line up. -Use solder and flux to tin connecting traces and solder them together. --Tape or glue beneath a glass plate for a strong, level heating surface

I am building a torsion box using corrugated plastic panel, and I find that I need a little someting to add rigidity to the joints. This thing acts as a 'cap' for each of the joints in such a torsion box. It can be used without glue, or you can actually glue it in place. The .scad has some easy parameters so you can select the gap size, and various lengths of things. Similarly, you can decide whether you want to have a hole in the middle of the thing, or not. This particular project was inspired by a project in my daughter's art class. NOTE: test_corners.scad is just for display purposes. There is nothing printable there really. It shows how the connector can be used in a torsion box construction. GITHUB: https://github.com/Wiladams/TorsionBox

1) Edit the .scad file to fit the width of your material. Change the 'gap' parameter.
2) Print as many as you need, typically one per joint
3) Assemble your torsion box, and place one cap over each joint
4) Rejoice!

title: Cable comb - perfect tool for easy and professional cable management

description.text: Cable comb. With this tool, you can easy organize large amounts of (ethernet) cables into neat cable bundles. Please watch this YouTube video on how to do this: https://youtu.be/-cFToZt_KzI. The tool can be used for bundling up to 35 cables with a thickness of 5mm. Holes and slots have a diameter of 6mm. The comb is tested on Cat5 ethernet cables, I assume Cat5e will work fine as well. I have designed this thing in Solidworks and exported it to STL format with an accuracy of 0.02mm. The design has taken 0.5mm play in account for a nice fit of the two parts. I have uploaded both the STL and the Solidworks source files. Feel free to modify the files to create your own perfect cable comb. Please take into account that this thing is published with a GNU-GPL license.

Before starting your print, measure the thickness of the cables for which you want to use the cable comb. The STL files provided have a slot thickness of 6mm, which is great for 5mm thick cables. If you are using thicker or thinner cables, scaling the cable comb may be a good idea. The slots should be a little wider than the thickness of your cables, in order to get the cables flow smooth through the cable comb. But also, the slots should not be too wide, to prevent cables from revolving around each other within a slot. Having the slot ~25% wider than the cable diameter should work fine.
  • Open the components in your slicing software (I used Cura) and rotate the objects to make them lay flat.
  • If needed, scale the objects with a factor [cable diameter in mm] / 5. Scaling should be done in at least the X and Y direction, the Z direction is optional.
  • On the comb I used a 25% infill which gave good results, so I recommend an infill of 20-25% on the comb. Support is not needed on this part
  • On the lock I used a 15% infill which gave very strong results, so I guess anything between 10% and 20% should be perfectly fine. Support on this part is not absolutely needed, but could give nicer looking results if you do not have an object cooling fan. I did not use any support.
  • Depending on your 3D-printer, a brim may be useful on both parts.
  • I used a 0.1mm layer height and a 0.3mm nozzle, but thicker layers and nozzles should work perfectly fine too.
    • If you use these steps for printing, your printed cable comb should turn out great! Really, this object is a very easy print, the only difficulty is the bridging on the locking part.

The OpenSCAD file Thin Nested Box.scad allows you to generate a box and lid to your specifications. I've pre-grenerated sizes 12mm through 40mm which should all nest within each other. The other OpenSCAD file, Thin Nested Boxes.scad will generate a range of boxes and lids for you. This is also a good test of your printer's precision.
